questions.explanation:
While Java strongly supports object-oriented programming, it retains some procedural programming characteristics. Primitive types like int, char, and boolean are not objects, and static methods can be called without creating an object instance. Pure object-oriented languages require all elements to be objects. Java provides wrapper classes for primitives to allow object-like interactions, but this doesn't make them true objects.

Example of non-object elements:
java
public class Example {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Static method call without object
        int number = Math.max(5, 10);

        // Primitive type, not an object
        int x = 5;
    }
}

Bytecode serves as a critical intermediate step in Java's compilation process, enabling platform independence. When a Java program is compiled, source code is transformed into bytecode, a low-level, highly optimized set of instructions that can be interpreted by any JVM, regardless of the underlying hardware or operating system. This approach allows Java's famous 'Write Once, Run Anywhere' principle.

Example of compilation process:
java
// Source Code (.java)
public class HelloWorld {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Hello, World!");
    }
}

// Compiled to Bytecode (.class)
// Executable by JVM on any platform

Java's garbage collection automatically handles memory management, reducing the risk of memory leaks and manual memory allocation errors. The process works by tracking object references and periodically identifying objects that are no longer accessible from the program's root set. While highly effective, garbage collection is not instantaneous and can introduce slight performance overhead.

Example of object reachability:
java
public class GarbageCollectionDemo {
    public void demonstrateReachability() {
        // Object becomes eligible for garbage collection
        String temp = new String("Temporary");
        temp = null; // No longer reachable
    }
}
